              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">Tariffs' diminishing role in federal revenue</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-14-2.jpg" alt="Tariffs' diminishing role in federal revenue" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Tariff revenue was once the primary source of U.S. federal receipts. However, its share of total revenue has significantly declined since the 19th century. Tariffs accounted for over 90% of government income in the early 1800s, but now they only contribute a negligible fraction.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The decline began in the late 19th century as the U.S. industrialized. Due to global trade disruptions, the reliance on tariffs weakened further during the Great Depression. By the mid-20th century, the federal government transitioned to broader revenue sources. Revenues such as payroll and income taxes started to fund growing expenditures.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          While strategically targeted tariffs remain a tool for protecting economic interests, economists warn that increasing reliance on tariffs for revenue could exacerbate income inequality and distort the economy.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
