          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is the Triffin dilemma?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-14-3.jpg" alt="What is the Triffin dilemma?" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000"> 
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The Triffin dilemma is a problem faced by countries using currencies as global reserve currencies, like the US dollar. These countries must balance their domestic economy with the world’s need for their currency.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The country has to trade deficits to meet global demand, which means importing more than it exports so the world gets enough of its currency. However, doing this for too long increases debt and can cause people to lose trust in the currency’s value. If the country tries to reduce deficits to protect its currency, it creates less global currency, which can slow down the global economy.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">For example, during the Bretton Woods era, the US had to provide enough dollars for global trade, leading to large deficits. Over time, this weakened confidence in the dollar and contributed to the collapse of the fixed exchange rate system.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
